---
import FaqAccordion from '@/components/FaqAccordion.astro';
---

<FaqAccordion
  heading="Frequently Asked Questions"
  items={[
    {
      question: "What is Semaglutide?",
      answer_html: "<p>Semaglutide is an FDA-approved medication that belongs to a class of drugs called GLP-1 receptor agonists. It works by mimicking a hormone that targets areas of the brain involved in appetite regulation, helping you feel fuller longer and reducing hunger. Originally developed for treating type 2 diabetes, it has shown remarkable effectiveness for weight management.</p>",
    },
    {
      question: "How does Semaglutide help with weight loss?",
      answer_html: "<p>Semaglutide works in multiple ways to support weight loss:</p><ul><li>Slows stomach emptying, helping you feel full longer after eating</li><li>Reduces appetite and hunger signals in the brain</li><li>Decreases food cravings, particularly for high-fat foods</li><li>Helps regulate blood sugar levels</li><li>Supports feeling satisfied with smaller portions</li></ul>",
    },
    {
      question: "How much weight can I expect to lose with Semaglutide?",
      answer_html: "<p>Clinical studies have shown that people taking Semaglutide, combined with lifestyle modifications, typically lose 15-20% of their body weight over 68 weeks. Individual results vary based on starting weight, adherence to dietary and exercise recommendations, and other health factors. Dr. Menon will help set realistic expectations based on your specific situation.</p>",
    },
    {
      question: "How is Semaglutide administered?",
      answer_html: "<p>Semaglutide is administered as a once-weekly subcutaneous injection. At Menon Medispa, Dr. Aditi Menon will provide comprehensive training on self-administration or can administer the injection for you during office visits. The medication is typically started at a lower dose and gradually increased to minimize side effects.</p>",
    },
    {
      question: "What side effects might I experience?",
      answer_html: "<p>Common side effects of Semaglutide may include:</p><ul><li>Nausea (most common, especially when starting treatment)</li><li>Diarrhea</li><li>Vomiting</li><li>Constipation</li><li>Abdominal pain</li><li>Headache</li></ul><p>Most side effects are mild to moderate and tend to decrease over time. Dr. Menon employs a gradual dose escalation strategy to minimize these effects and will work with you to manage any discomfort.</p>",
    },
  ]}
/>
